.\}
.SS MAKE_KEY
.PP
.proto_make_key
.PP
Create a key table that contains sorted two-field rows of a key value
and a row index to the source table from which the key is created.
.PP
The key table is intended for use by the
.B seek_key
action to conduct fast binary searches and enable ISAM (indexed
sequential action method) access to the rows of the source table.
.PP
The key table can also be passed to
.B walk_rows
with the
.B -k
option to use the key order for calling the
.B walk_rows
callback function.
.arg_handle
.TP
.I new_handle_name
name to use for the new key handle
.TP
.B -i
enable integer sorting method
.TP
.B -n
enable case-insensitive by making key values lower-case
.TP
.B -r
enable reverse sorting (descending order)
.TP
.BI "-c " column_index
alternate table column to use for sorting the key.
The default value, if no
.B -c
options is specified, is to use column index 0.
.IP
This option will be ignored if the
.B -f
option is also used.
.TP
.BI "-f " key_value_callback
is called by
.B make_key
for each row to get a computed key value.
.IP
This option takes precedence over the
.B -c
option.
.TP
.RI [ ... ]
optional extra arguments, as needed, to be transmitted to the
.I key_value_callback
for each row.
.PP
.TP
.B Key Value Callback Function
The
.B key_value_callback
function, if specified with the
.B -f
option, should be a script function that will be called for each
table row to request a constructed value to be used as the row's key.
.IP
The callback function will receive the following arguments:
.TS
tab(|);
l lx.
\(Do1|T{
a
.B result variable
name for a nameref variable to which the constructed key value will
be returned.
T}
\(Do2|T{
a
.B row array name
for a nameref variable containing a copy of the row's contents to
be used to construct the key value.
T}
\&...|T{
.B extra arguments
will follow
.I $2
as provided to the
.B make_key
action to aid with constructing the key value.
T}
.TE
.IP
When key values have all been collected, the key table will be sorted
on the key values.
